Explaining Our Data

Dataset Criteria

With our original concept we were attempting to find trends in the top music on Spotify, however when merging our original datasets we found many complications. Our original data sets were Top Spotify songs from 2010-2019-BY YEAR and Spotify top 10000 Streamed Songs which we thought would allow us to answer the main topic we were interested in. However, when merging we found that the only key we could use to merge was song name which resulted in complications. When merged together we had various repeats as some songs had the same name but written by different artists, and when we tried to eliminate these repeats we found that none of our filter methods kept any songs. With these issue we then decided to find new data sets. The ones we decided to select 30000 Spotify Songs and Spotify_1Million_Tracks. These data sets fit our criteria as we found a great way to merge the two using the track_name, which was unique for all of the values in each data set. We also believed that the variables the data sets contained would allow us to explore our question effectively.

Dataset Info

To find our data sets we stayed on Kaggle which was where our original data was from. We thought this was the best choice, as we belived we would find similar data sets when compared to our original one. On Kaggle is where we found 30000 Spotify Songs and Spotify_1Million_Tracks. For 30000 Spotify Songs there was only one person who collected it and they were Joakim Arvidsson. For Spotify_1Million_Tracks there were a total of 3 collectors who were Amintash Joshi, Vedant Das, and Amit Parolkar.The data was not restricted in any form it is freely available to anyone. The only real restriction would be needing a Kaggle account, but besided that it is open to everyone with a Kaggle account. Since there are no restrictions and the authors didn’t post any intention for its use, we believe that it can be used for any purpose. Both of the data sets contain various components of the music.

Dataset Components

The data sets each contain their own respectvie set of details for the music it contains. However in both data sets one row represents a distinct song with a specific name and artist.The main reason we chose both of these data sets was becasue they each contained the column track_id which is what we used for the merging key. The Spotify_1Million_Tracks contained 1159764 observations and 20 diffferent variables while the 30000 Spotify Songs had 32833 observations and 23 variables. Furthermore the columns we were interested in Spotify_1Million_Tracks were artist_name, popularity, year,and genre. For the 30000 Spotify Songs we were interested in the variables track_artist , mode, valance, energy, and duration_ms. The artist_name and track_artist column is in the form of a string in both sets and contain the name of the artist who wrote the specified song for the row. This column contains 64159 distinct artists in the Spotify_1Million_Tracks while it contains 10693 distinct artists in 30000 Spotify Songs. The year column is the release year for the specified song in Spotify_1Million_Tracks and is in the form of integers and ranges from 2000 to 2023. The popularity contains values from 0 to 100 and dictates how popular the song is, there isn’t much info on how they go about dictating the popularity which we were confused about. The genre column is in strings and contains the genre type the song is categorized in. There are a total of 82 genres the song can be categorized in. The mode variable represents if the song is in major (denoted by 1) or in minor (denoted by 0). Both valance and energy variables range from 0 to 1.0. Higher valance values represent more positive emotions while a lower one represent negative ones. For energy higher values represent a faster, louder, and noisier song while lower ones represent slower, mellow, and more silent songs. The duration_ms is an integer form and is just the length of the song in milliseconds. For the data set we selected there was no missing data as we believe Spotify does a good job at keeping track of all of the songs they keep, especially since the songs were more recent. For this reason we didn’t find any non-plausible values nor quality issues in our data.

Final Dataset

Our final data set was created by using inner_join merging with a join key of the track_id for each data set. This left us with a total of 4796 observations we included 25 variables. The important variables that were included were the ones mentioned before.

Methods

The most important variables that we used for our analyses were - year, genre, popularity, mode, energy, valence, duration, and artist name. The reason why we used these variables was because they enabled us to find correlations between each other that would help us in conveying our story. We experimented with other variables as well, however, though they did not show anything contradicting to our story, the evidence or proof of explanation that we received from them was relatively poor and hence we ignored them. Our choice of variables was a mix of continuous data, which provided an accurate way of quantifying and understanding the data itself, and categorical data, which enabled us to quickly recognize trends, changes and patterns based on inter-related variable.

After importing the two data sets - Spotify_1Million_Tracks and 30000 Spotify Songs into R, the first step we did was to use the head() function in R to understand the different variables and the observations that was in the two data sets. This enabled us to identify the merge key that would efficiently merge the 2 data sets. We also identified the variables that would be useful as well as those that would not and removed variables that would prove not useful for our purposes by using the dplyr function select() to choose every column other than the ones we did not want. The columns that we eliminated were - _playlist_name, playlist_id,__playlist_genre, and playlist_subgenre_. Once we agreed on this, we merged the two data sets using inner_join(). The merge key for this merge was the variable containing the name of the songs which was called ‘track_name’ in both the data sets. We used inner_join() between the 1 million and the 30000 song data set to ensure that the final data set will result in a table with no NA or NULL values. This minimized our observations from 1 million to just about 6000.

After merging the 2 data sets, we observed that there were certain rows that were duplicated even though all the oberservations for the different variables were the same. Therefore, in order to remove the duplicates, we used the unique() function in R to perform this task. We also learnt that there were two popularity variables, one from each of the original data set, that were not equal to each other. Hence, we eliminated one of them, namely the one from the 30000 songs data, because we thought that the data set with the 1 million songs had better popularity ranking than the 30000 due to larger collections of songs in that data set. In order, to make our analysis more interesting with trends relating to popularity, we decided to keep all observations that had a popularity rank of 60 or higher using the dplyr function filter(). The final cleaning was to remove the year 2020 because graphing certain relationship showed that the observations from 2020 acted as outliers to the analyses. The final data set that we used for our analyses was about 1300 observations and 24 variables.

For processing data, our method of approach was to identify continuous variable and categorical variables and create new variables that contain more specific information according to what we wanted to analyze. We used multiple dplyr functions such as filter(), select(), mutate(), summarize(), groupby() to enable us to narrow down the large data set for processing and visualization purposes. filter() function was used to filter out the data set by genre. We used groupby() to group distinct observations in a variable together in order to apply other functions such as summarize(), and mutate(), using which we were able to create our own variables and compare them to the existing variables. To compare different variables together we used the ggplot library to plot the graphs of different types of graph such as scatter plots, box plots, histograms, and line plots. For two continuous variables we used scatter plots and line plots which allowed us to identify the trend in the data, and applying a linear regression model to this type of plot allowed us to predict the future trend of the two variables. We used box plots because they enabled us see the relationship between categorical variables and continuous variables. Histograms were used to find the average distribution of continuous variables and understand what values are most likely for each variable.

The main statistical methods that we used was mean(). It enabled us to view a group of data as one concise value that helped in analyses of data. Another function we used to study the data was range(), to study the either extent of a variable. A complex statistical method we used was the linear regression model in geom_smooth() which was a part of the ggplot library. This model enabled us to study the trends of the data that we plotted as well as predict what would be the most likely direction of the trend.

Question 2 : Is there a relationship between rise of artist and genre popularity ?

Artist count per year - by genre

Most of our earlier graphs focused on the song count which we thought was not very indicative on artist success. The first thing we wanted to explore was the number of distinct artist who wrote popular songs. We thought this would be more indicative of artist success as multiple popular songs could be written by 1 artist. Using the summarize functions, group_by using year and genre, and the n_distinct function to create a new variable tot_artist which represents the total number of distinct artist that wrote popular music that year.

Through this graph we see that over time more distinct artist are making popular songs. We believe this indicates some potential for artist to be successful in the popular genres. However, we want to see if any of the genres could be more successful in specific genres, so we decided to look at how many distinct artist make up a popular genre.

Distinct Artist in genre by year

To find what we were interested in we used the group_by function with the genre, and summarize to create total_artist which is just the total count of distinct artist in a genre.

From this bar graph we see that dance genre has the most distinct artist. This made us think that someone might have the most success if they made a song that fit in the dance genre. However, we wanted to see new artist data so we decided to make a data set called break_out which would show an artist and when they made their first popular song. This would show us how many new artist actually made it (wrote a popular song) and were succesful.

Number of break out artist per year

To perform what question we were interested we employed similar sunctions as we had before. We first used group_by with artist_name which we then used mutate to create a new column called break_out_year representing the first year a distinct artist wrote a popular song. This was done by finding the min of each artist group’s year column. After creating this we further employed group_by using break_out_year and genre to make the column new_artist_count which was the number of new artist who broke out (made their first popular song) for a specified year. This was done using summarize and n_distinct of artist_name.

We observe a difference in trends and see that hip-hop genre might be the best way to be a break out artist. We believe this because there are more new artists who made it in the hip-hop genre during current times.

New artist vs old artist

Something we further thought would be useful was to see the trend of new artist vs the old artist. We used a left_join by year matching with break_out_year and the genre columns matching. We then further changed the tot_artist variable ,which was the count of distinct artist per year, using the mutate function to be changed to tot_artist minus new_artist_count . This would get our tot_artist to be the count of old artists. We then used pivot_longer to create a longer table which createcd a new varible artist_type which would say wether the count (number of artist) was “old” artist or “new” artist.

For this plot we did have a missing variable as for the earlies year there was not previous year that could be used. From this we see that the count has a larger difference in the hip-hop genre. For this reason we believed that hip-hop is the best genre for a new upcoming artist to take.

Q3 : “What are the basic elements of a song that could result in it becoming a popular song?”

Through this question we hoped to provide new and current music artist with guidelines on what the different components of songs should be so that they have a higher likelihood of making a song that would become popular. The 3 elements of music that we focused on were mode, Valence, Energy,and Duration.

Mode indicates the modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. Major is represented by 1 and minor is 0. Our results show that on average the more popular songs are the more major the mode of the track is. This helps the artist take the most fundamental decision when it comes to making a song.

Valence is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry). Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy. In our analysis, we first wanted to know the relationship between the valence of a song as well as the energy, and using a linear regression model we identified that for all three genres of dance, hip-hop, and pop, there was a positive correlation between them. This meant that more energetic and upbeat songs were usually happier and cheerful whereas mellow and sober songs were more sad, depressed and angry. Using a scatter plot between valence and year variable, we found out that more recent songs for all of three genres are decreasing in valence (more sad, depressed and angry songs). Applying the same analysis to energy and year, we found an interesting trend that though the valence decreased in more recent years, the enrgy for the songs mostly stayed the same and for the dance genre, it interestingly increased. This did not comply with our previous analysis of the relationship between energy and valency of songs and we thought that this might be due to a few outliers in the graph and also less amount of sample data. For the relationship between valency and energy of a song and popularity, the most popular songs had extreme values of valency and energy depicting that songs that conveyed true, deep and raw emotions were super popular whereas songs with mid valency and energy were less popular.

Duration is the length of the song in milliseconds. The average length for each genre was:

Mean song duration for Dance is 2.1218539^{5} ms which is 3 mins and 32 secs.

Mean song duration for Pop is 2.174247^{5} ms which is 3 mins and 37 secs.

Mean song duration for Hip-hop is 2.2300592^{5} ms which is 3 mins and 43 secs.

So as a growing music artist or a new artist, our analysis reveals that creating a song in the genre of dance, or pop, or hip-hop with a major modality, artfully weaved with true and deep emotions expressed in both lyrics and music with the duration of 3 mins and 30 secs would make an artist more likely to become more popular.
